<NOTE>For Release Friday, Jan. 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, Jan. 19th, the 19th day of 1990. There are 346
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On Jan. 19, 1807, Robert E. Lee, the commander-in-chief of the
Confederate armies, was born in Stratford, Va.
   On this date:
   In 1736, James Watt, the inventor of the steam engine, was born
in Scotland.
   In 1809, author Edgar Allan Poe was born in Boston.
   In 1825, Ezra Daggett and his nephew, Thomas Kensett, obtained a
patent for their process of storing food in tin cans.
   In 1853, Verdi's opera ``Il Trovatore'' premiered in Rome.
   In 1861, Georgia seceded from the Union.
   In 1937, millionaire Howard Hughes set a transcontinental air
record by flying his monoplane from Los Angeles to Newark, N.J., in
seven hours, 28 minutes and 25 seconds.
   In 1955, a presidential news conference was filmed for
television for the first time, with the permission of President
Eisenhower.
   In 1977, in one of his last official acts of office, President
Ford pardoned Iva Toguri D'Aquino, an American who had made wartime
broadcasts for Japan as ``Tokyo Rose.''
   In 1979, former Attorney General John N. Mitchell was released
on parole after serving 19 months at a federal prison at Maxwell
Air Force Base in Alabama.
   In 1984, the California Supreme Court rejected a petition from
quadriplegic Elizabeth Bouvia, who wanted to starve herself to
death in a public hospital.
   In 1987, Guy Hunt became Alabama's first Republican governor
since 1874 as he was sworn into office, succeeding George C.
Wallace and marking the end of a political era.
   Ten years ago: Former Supreme Court Justice William O. Douglas,
who had served on the nation's highest court from 1939 to 1975,
died in Washington at age 81.
   Five years ago: The entertainment world turned out in
Washington, D.C., on the eve of President Reagan's second
inauguration, as celebrities gathered for a two-hour gala.
   One year ago: The Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted
unanimously to recommend that the full Senate approve the
nomination of James A. Baker to be secretary of state.
   Today's Birthdays: Actress Jean Stapleton is 67. Actor Fritz
Weaver is 64. PBS newsman Robert MacNeil is 59. Movie director
Richard Lester is 58. Singer Phil Everly is 51. Actress Shelley
Fabares is 46. Singer Dolly Parton is 44. ABC newswoman Ann Compton
is 43. Singer Robert Palmer is 41. Actor Desi Arnaz Jr.is 37.
   Thought for Today: ``If you want to know what God thinks of
money, look at the people he gives it to.'' _ New England saying.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Friday, Jan. 19</NOTE>
